        "MasterPrompt":  "Create a 3:2 premium 3D typography-based travel poster for Chiang Mai, using luxury editorial destination advertising fused with realistic sculptural letterform architecture.The city name “CHIANG MAI” must be the dominant subject, occupying most of the canvas. Build the letters as large, realistic, three-dimensional sculptural forms made from glossy painted material, polished ceramic, soft plaster, carved teak wood, aged sandstone, sunlit temple surfaces, and Lanna architectural materials. Each letter should physically transform into Chiang Mai’s identity: temple rooflines, lantern motifs, mountain silhouettes, traditional arches, wooden balconies, old city walls, handcrafted patterns, tropical foliage, market details, and northern Thai architectural forms must grow directly out of the letterforms.Landmarks should feel architecturally integrated, not pasted behind or around the word. A temple spire may rise from a vertical stem, a lantern bridge may connect two letters, a Lanna roof may form the curve of a rounded letter, traditional wooden windows may be embedded into the letter faces, and carved northern Thai ornaments may flow along the typography edges.Use a low-angle three-quarter camera view so the typography feels monumental, cinematic, premium, and welcoming. Place the 3D city-name sculpture slightly low in the frame, filling the central and lower portions of the poster, with generous negative space above.At the top header, add a refined horizontal row of faded landmark symbols related to Chiang Mai: tiny vector icons or translucent architectural glyphs of Doi Suthep temple, lanterns, elephants, traditional umbrellas, mountain lines, old city gates, and tropical leaves. Add each landmark name below its icon. Keep all faded, elegant, and secondary like premium magazine header details.Remove any visible sun from the top-left corner. Use bright natural daylight with a soft key light from the upper-left, gentle fill light, clean highlights, subtle ambient occlusion, and soft contact shadows beneath the letters. The lighting should feel cheerful, fresh, warm, and editorial, not dark or overly cinematic.Use a bright Chiang Mai-adaptive palette:warm saffron orange,terracotta clay,palm green,teak brown,soft ivory,river blue,lantern gold,and muted tropical turquoise.Keep colors clean, optimistic, premium, and controlled.Add subtle editorial text elements to improve the poster:small uppercase header text such as “DESTINATION SERIES”, a tiny location code like “CNX / 01”, delicate vertical divider lines, a minimal footer line such as “VISIT CHIANG MAI”, and small microtype coordinates or issue number near the bottom edge. These text elements must remain quiet and secondary so the large 3D city name stays the hero.Background should be clean and spacious with a soft atmospheric sky gradient, delicate tropical clouds, or abstract warm color field only. Do not place extra landmarks in the background; all major city identity must come from the typography itself, except the faded symbolic header row.Style: premium editorial travel advertising, luxury magazine cover, realistic 3D typographic sculpture, bright modern optimism, cheerful wanderlust, northern Thai cultural identity, clean art direction.Negative prompt: avoid generic travel posters, separate landmark collages, landmarks pasted behind text, flat typography, cluttered backgrounds, visible sun in the top-left corner, excessive icons, dark cinematic lighting, muddy colors, cheap souvenir aesthetics, unreadable city name, distorted letters, random gradients, noisy textures, stock-template layouts, and overdecorated tourist graphics.",
