        "Recipe":  "• เนื้อหา/เป้าหมายบทเรียน [SUBJECT]: หัวข้อบทเรียนหรือชุดข้อมูลเปรียบเทียบ 4 มิติ   • รูปแบบและสไตล์ศิลปะ [STYLE]: High Detail Readability / Polished Concept Sheet   • โครงสร้างการจัดวาง [LAYOUT]: Multi-panel Grid Layout with clear typography",
        "MasterPrompt":  "make the image from this prompt. Then create a dramatic editorial infographic poster in the style of a National Geographic feature — but for iconic stadiums. The most powerful and recognizable aerial or interior image of [Anfield Liverpool ] is the full-bleed atmospheric hero filling the entire poster top to bottom, dramatically lit and color-graded in tones that match the stadium’s identity and club or nation colors. Oversized bold typography with the stadium name dominates the upper portion in a font matching the stadium’s prestige and character. Text and graphic panels float naturally over the image as editorial overlays — not boxed magazine layouts. Include: construction year and architect, total capacity, location and city, major events hosted, record attendance, most famous moments, renovation history, cost to build, nicknames, and 3 surprising lesser-known facts. A small location map inset. A timeline of the stadium’s greatest moments along the bottom. Color palette and mood drawn entirely from the stadium’s own identity and colors. No white background, no magazine grid, no boxed sections. Everything layered organically over the full-bleed hero image. Aspect ratio 4:5. Dense, tactile, cinematic, unmistakably that stadium.Data used for image: Anfield: The Cathedral of FootballAnfield Stadium stands as one of the most culturally significant structures in world sport. Rather than abandoning its historical foundations for a modern suburban arena, Liverpool F.C. chose a path of architectural evolution, weaving the club\u0027s 19th-century soul into a 21st-century sporting fortress.  Architectural Architecture \u0026 DimensionsBuilt \u0026 Opened: 1884  Original Construction Cost: Funded initially via private land leases under John Orrell; recent modern standalone stand expansions exceeded £231 million collectively.Original Architect: Uncredited local builders (1884); iconic early additions engineered by the legendary stadium architect Archibald Leitch (1906 Spion Kop).  Modern Expansion Designers: KSS Group (Main Stand, 2016).  Current Seating Capacity: 61,276  Pitch Surface: Desso GrassMaster hybrid turf (polypropylene fibers interwoven with natural grass).Field Dimensions: 101 by 68 meters (110.5 yd × 74.4 yd).  Location: Anfield Road, Liverpool, Merseyside, England, L4 0TH.  The Four StandsThe Spion Kop: A towering single-tier structure holding 12,390 passionate supporters. Named after the battle ridge of Spion Kop in South Africa, it stands as a unified wall of red.  The Main Stand: One of the largest single all-seater stands in European football, expanded in 2016 to hold 20,500 people across three tiers. It features a massive cantilevered roof ensuring completely unobstructed sightlines.  Sir Kenny Dalglish Stand: Originally known as the Kemlyn Road Stand, this two-tier structure houses executive suites and accommodates over 11,000 fans.  Anfield Road End: Positioned opposite the Kop, its multi-tiered architecture was completely redeveloped between 2021 and 2024 to finalize the stadium\u0027s push past the 61,000 capacity threshold.  Major Events \u0026 Historical RecordsRecord Attendance: 61,905 spectators on February 2, 1952, during an FA Cup 4th-round tie against Wolverhampton Wanderers.  International Tournaments: Hosted four matches during UEFA Euro 1996 (three group games and a quarter-final).  Other Major Events: Trans-Atlantic Rugby League matches, boxing championships, and historic music concerts featuring local and international icons.The Fortress Factor: Liverpool remained completely unbeaten at home in the league across 11 different individual seasons, including structural stretches where opponents went years without winning a domestic fixture on Anfield\u0027s turf.  3 Surprising Lesser-Known FactsThe Blue Origins: Anfield was not built for Liverpool F.C. It opened in 1884 as the home ground of their cross-town rivals, Everton F.C. Everton even won their first league title right on Anfield\u0027s pitch in 1891 before a bitter rent dispute with land owner John Houlding forced them to move to Goodison Park. Left with an empty stadium, Houlding founded Liverpool F.C. to fill the void.  The Camouflage Seating: Legendary manager Bob Paisley once insisted that the Anfield Road End be fitted with multi-colored seats instead of a solid red block. He believed that when players wore their all-red home kits, a solid background of empty red seats made it harder for them to spot passing lines in their peripheral vision.  An Engineering Illusion: During the massive 2014–2016 expansion, engineers built the towering, 650-ton steel frame of the new Main Stand directly around and over the existing, historical structure. This highly complex engineering feat allowed Liverpool to continue playing all their home games at full capacity without interrupting a single matchday while the giant shell rose behind it.  Timeline of Greatest Moments  1884: Anfield opens its gates to the public for the first time.  1892: Liverpool F.C. is formed and plays its inaugural friendly match on the pitch, defeating Rotherham Town 7–1.  1906: Architect Archibald Leitch completes a new bank of terracing along Walton Breck Road, officially named the \"Spion Kop\" to honor soldiers lost in the Boer War.  1928: The Kop is extended under a massive new roof, allowing up to 30,000 standing fans to pack into a single tier.  1957: The introduction of pylon floodlights allows regular nighttime European fixtures to take place.  1960s: Manager Bill Shankly installs the famous \"This Is Anfield\" plaque in the player tunnel to instill psychological fear in visiting opponents.  1982: The iconic Shankly Gates are erected along Anfield Road, featuring the club\u0027s eternal anthem lyrics, \"You\u0027ll Never Walk Alone\".  1994: Prompted by the safety regulations of the Taylor Report following the Hillsborough tragedy, the Kop is demolished and rebuilt into an all-seater stand.  2016: The state-of-the-art Main Stand expansion is unveiled, dramatically altering the city\u0027s skyline.  2024: The completion of the Anfield Road End expansion officially pushes matchday capacity over the 61,000 threshold.",
